Yet, although filled\nwith good intentions,
our discipline has\nbeen, and to this day,
is, continuously faced with\nambivalence, contradictions,
and difficult ethical\ndilemmas for which
there are no easy answers.
As geographer Don\nMitchell has written,
"Landscape hides all kinds of\neconomic and social inequities
beneath its\nscenographic beauty."
And while recognizing\nthe imperative
to expose the dark\nside of landscape,
I am equally interested in the\nunfinished, unresolved project
of landscape.
By this, I mean the\nproductive effects
that this ambivalence\ncan have in our work--
how it moves us to innovate,\nto navigate between conflicting
aims, to search for\na better relationship
with the natural world.
For this, we rely on the help\nof historians, and especially,
on our Aaron Sachs, whose\nwork probes these difficult
