in the past few weeks, with\none clear, concrete example
of an environmental-justice\nformulation that
goes all the way back\nto the 17th century.
The key thinker here is a\nrelatively obscure Englishman
named Gerrard Winstanley,\nwho, for a few centuries,
was mostly lost to history.
But his writings\nwere rediscovered
in the late 20th century.
And I think it's fair to\ncharacterize them retroactively
as a series of\nenvironmental-justice
manifestos, delivered during\nthe English Civil War,
mostly in 1649 And 1650.
A less anachronistic\nway to describe them
might be as\n"passionate arguments
to protect the commons for\nthe use of the landless poor."
He was he was a\npamphleteer, basically.
This is one of his pamphlets.
And you can, just\nfrom that language,
start to see what\nhe's getting at.
At the beginning of April 1649,\nWinstanley and about two dozen
others started\ndigging and planting
on St. George's Hill\nin Walton on Thames,
the area was considered\na commons, or waste,
a piece of land neither\nowned nor regularly planted,
and therefore traditionally\navailable to poor people
as a place where they might\ngather wood or graze livestock.
But Winstanley and the\nso-called "diggers"
were looking not\nonly to solidify,
but also to broaden the rights\nof so-called "commoners,"
in line with the democratizing\ntendencies of the English Civil
War--
the word "commoner" is\na very interesting one,
which, for a long\ntime, I just thought
of as indicating an\nordinary person-- not
a member of the\nnobility or the clergy,
but a member of the Third\nEstate-- a common person.
But I think it's\njust as important
to think of "commoner"\nas meaning somebody
with rights to the commons.
These diggers burned\naway some of the heath,
plowed the dirt, planted corn,\nbeans, parsnips, and carrots,
declaring their\nintention, quote,
"to eat our bread together\nby the sweat of our brows."
Basically, it was an\nexperimental commune.
And they invited poor people\nfrom around the country
to join them, encouraging\nthem not only to claim land
for their own use, but also,\nto withhold their labor
from the local lords.
The next month, May of\nthat same year, parliament
declared that the Kingdom\nof England was no more.
This is the English\nCivil War again.
And the nation was now\nofficially a commonwealth.
In this context that\nword meant mostly
that the monarchy had been\nabolished, King Charles having
been beheaded,\nand that a new era
of wider political\nparticipation had begun.
But the word "commonwealth"\nalso resonated
with earlier meanings.
In the previous century,\nas large landlords
had launched what became the\nEnclosure movement, claiming
more and more common lands\nas their own for profit,
a counter-movement of\npoor people had arisen.
And they called themselves\n"commonwealth men,"
emphasizing the responsibility\nof the rich to help the poor
and attacking this new\ntrend toward profit-seeking.
The lords had lost some\nof their military power,
and they were looking\nfor more economic power.
We can think of these\ncommonwealth men
in the 16th century as\nforming a movement in line
with some of the ideas expressed\nin Thomas More's Utopia, which
was published in 1516.
And if you haven't read it or\nhaven't looked at it recently,
I'll just remind you that on the\nsmall island nation of Utopia,
all men and women must work.
There are no idle\nlandholders, because there
is no private property.
And in fact, there had been\nno private property in England
until these lords started\nthe Enclosure movement.
Winstanley was quick\nto seize on these older
meanings of the\nword "commonwealth,"
as he argued that the\nnew version of England,
to be true to its\nidentity, would
have to reign in the wealthy and\nensure that all commoners had
free access to the commons.
The poor, he pointed out,\nhad contributed greatly
to the overthrow of the\nmonarchy-- paying taxes,
serving in armies.
And the parliamentarians\nhad indeed
promised them a new freedom.
The language Winstanley\nused in making
these arguments of course, comes\nfrom traditions in theology,
and philosophy, and politics\nspecific to his time and place.
And yet, I also want to argue\nthat his discourse represents
something both new\nand incredibly durable
in its articulation\nof the environment
as a shared resource to\nwhich all human beings have
an equal claim.
"Let us dig on the\nhill," he says,
quote, "that we may\nwork in righteousness
and lay the foundation of making\nthe earth a common treasury
for all, both rich and\npoor, that everyone that
is born in the land may be fed\nby the earth, his mother, that
brought him forth,\nnot enclosing any part
into any particular hand, but\nall as one man working together
and feeding together, not\none lording over another,
but all looking upon each other\nas equals in the creation,
so that our maker\nmay be glorified
in the work of his own hands,
and that everyone may see he\nis no respecter of persons
but equally loves\nhis whole creation
and hates nothing but\nthe serpent, which
is covetousness."
Unquote.
"Let us dig on the\nhill," he says,
"and practice\nusufruct," a word that
arose in English at about the\nsame time as "commonwealth,"
"to show that what matters\nis not ownership, but use,
to show that, in fact, private\nproperty is a curse, since,"
quote, "those that buy and\nsell land and are landlords
have got it either by\noppression, or murder,
or theft.
"Let us dig on the\nhill," he says,
"because in the\nbeginning of time,
the great creator\nreason made the Earth
to be a common treasury to\npreserve beasts, birds, fishes,
and man, the lord that was to\ngovern this creation, for man
had domination given to him over\nthe beasts, birds, and fishes.
But not one word was\nspoken in the beginning
that one branch of mankind\nshould rule over another."
Remember man-versus-man?
Man-versus-man is\nthe real problem.
"Go about your\nbusiness, you landlords,
and let us dig in peace.
We told you that we\nwere not against any
that would have magistrates\nand laws to govern
as the nations of the\nworld are governed.
But as for our parts, we\nshall need neither the one
or the other in that\nnature of government,
for as our land is commons,\nso our cattle is to be common,
and our corn and fruits of\nthe earth common, and are not
to be brought and sold among\nus, but to remain a standing
portion of livelihood\nto us and our children,
without that\ncheating entanglement
of buying and selling.
And we shall not\narrest one another."
OK, I could quote Winstanley\nuntil the cows come back
from their common grazing area.
But you get the idea.
And of course, you can predict\nthat his diggers would not
be able to hold out very long.
There were, in fact,\na few other communes
that arose around the country.
But in every case,\nthe local gentry
came down really, really\nhard on the rebels,
attacking them on\nhorseback, setting fire
to their crops and huts, driving\nthem away within a few months,
because these planters\non the commons
represented such a direct threat\nto the protocapitalist system.
And remarkably, at\nexactly the same time,
similar scenarios\nwere playing out
across the ocean\nin the Americas,
as colonizers\ngradually encroached
on the various commons\nmanaged by native groups.
Native Americans\nof the 17th century
did not leave behind much\nin the way of documents.
But based on the\nknowledge that we do have
of their land-management\npractices and cultural-belief
systems--
many of these groups, anyway--
we can note the almost uncanny\nparallels to Winstanley vision.
These native groups did\nnot live in a wilderness
as John Locke would\nargue, but in fact,
under a regime of collectively\nowned property, to which
all human beings were\nbound under an ethic
of careful, equitable,\nsustainable use.
Now of course, there\nare limitations
to Winstanley discourse.
We can't just lift it and\nuse it in the 21st century.
He was dealing with a pretty\nhomogeneous population
of white Christian men.
I don't think he ever\nchallenged the authority
of the patriarchal family.
He consistently did endorse\na universal egalitarianism,
but we're left to wonder\nwhether he would have applied it
to people of color, like the\nblack Africans already being
enslaved by his countrymen, or\nthe Native Americans already
being dispossessed\nby his countrymen.
I think Murray\nBookchin surely would
have approved of\nWinstanley invocation
of a kind of primitive\nsolidarity and anarchism.
Still, to most modern ears,\nthis form of communalism
probably sounds\nromantic and naive.
I just have to admit that\nI've found it very helpful
for myself to travel\nback to a time
before the discourses of\ncapitalism and colonialism
had been fully\nformed and justified,
before many people took\nAdam Smith and David
Hume for granted and assumed\nthat all human beings would
always just dominate,\nand accumulate,
and covet, according to\ntheir own self-interest.
The idea of the\ntragedy of the commons
has been thoroughly debunked\nby now-- most notably
by the Nobel-Prize winning\neconomist, Elinor Ostrom.
But many environmentalists\nstill assume
that it's impossible\nto protect any commons,
because each individual\nhuman being is
inherently bent on\nconsumption and destruction.
For me, Winstanley at\nleast represents a moment
when it was still possible\nto invoke the collective
over the individual, the common\ngood over private advantage,
when it was still\npossible to speak
of a universal right to direct\nsubsistence from the earth.
Winstanley often uses the word\n"livelihood" in this context.
It's even important to me\nto consider the implications
of Winstanley's embrace\nof humanity's domination
over nature.
And I'm sure many of\nyou noted that language.
Some environmentalists\nstill blame
